{"key":"processedPost-10186533","value":{"id":10186533,"first":10181434,"last":10186789,"when":1240016789,"utime":"04/18/09 04:06 AM","content":"FAE is the number ONE pinning trigger.&nbsp; Once the substrate is fully colonized, it doesn't matter if contaminant spores get on it or not.&nbsp; You want fresh air and lots of it.&nbsp; I'm no fan of the monotub type grows, but the least you can do is remove the polyfill at full colonization.&nbsp; The idea that removing the polyfill allows contaminants in is not based on fact.&nbsp; The lid on storage totes is not airtight, so 'contaminants' get in from day one.&nbsp; The polyfill is there to restrict air exchange during colonization.&nbsp; It has nothing to do with being a filter.<br /><br />Remove the polyfill for fruiting, and mist as required to replace moisture that evaporates from your substrates.&nbsp; <br /><br />Lighting from the sides is fine.&nbsp; If it tweaks your butt to see your mushrooms growing towards the light, simply rotate your tubs every day or two.<br />RR","title":"Re: Stacking tubs/lighting?"}}